com.googlecode.cqengine.resultset.iterator
Class MarkableIterator<T>

java.lang.Object
  com.googlecode.cqengine.resultset.iterator.MarkableIterator<T>
All Implemented Interfaces:
Iterator<T>
public class MarkableIterator<T>
extends Object
implements Iterator<T>

An iterator which wraps a backing iterator, and which adds support for mark(int) and reset(), similar to an InputStream.

When mark(int) is called, the iterator will start buffering the objects it serves, up to the given limit. When reset() is called, the iterator will start to replay the objects it buffered since mark(int) was called. When the iterator has then finished replaying the buffered objects, it will continue to read from the backing iterator and add them to the buffer, until mark(int) is called again.

To repeatedly replay objects from a certain point, call reset() immediately followed by mark(int).
To stop buffering objects, call mark with readLimit 0.

Author:
niall.gallagher

mark

public void mark(int readLimit)
Starts buffering objects from the backing iterator so that they may be replayed when reset() is called.

Parameters:
readLimit - The maximum limit of objects that can be read before the mark position becomes invalid.
See Also:
InputStream.mark(int)

reset

public void reset()
Repositions this iterator to the position at the time the mark method was last called.

If the mark method has not been called since the iterator was created, or the number of objects read from the iterator since mark was last called is larger than the argument to mark at that last call, then an IllegalStateException will be thrown.

Otherwise, the iterator is reset to a state such that all the objects read since the most recent call to mark will be resupplied to subsequent callers of the next method, followed by any objects that otherwise would have been the next input data as of the time of the call to reset.

Throws:
IllegalStateException - If the iterator has not been marked or the mark has been invalidated
See Also:
InputStream.reset()
